with many skeptics over many years.

35
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:38,520
Myself, my role here is that I've

36
00:01:38,520 --> 00:01:42,160
been hosting conversations between skeptics and Christians

37
00:01:42,160 --> 00:01:43,080
for a number of years.

38
00:01:43,080 --> 00:01:45,480
In fact, over 15 years, some people

39
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:47,280
know me from The Unbelievable Show, which

40
00:01:47,280 --> 00:01:49,840
I hosted for 17 years or more.

41
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:51,920
And I'm currently engaged in some new projects.

42
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:54,920
And I'll be excited to tell you about those as well a little

43
00:01:54,920 --> 00:01:56,760
later on in the evening.

44
00:01:56,760 --> 00:01:59,240
But really, you're here to obviously see and hear

45
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:00,880
from John Lennox.

46
00:02:00,880 --> 00:02:03,640
So I'd like to invite both Samuel and John

47
00:02:03,640 --> 00:02:06,040
to join me on stage as they begin this evening.

48
00:02:06,040 --> 00:02:07,440
Do give them a round of applause.

49
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:21,880
Welcome everyone to Practical Wisdom,

50
00:02:21,880 --> 00:02:23,480
and thank you very much for joining us.

51
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:25,800
My name is Samuel Maruska, and today we're

52
00:02:25,800 --> 00:02:29,760
going to be talking about faith in God and science.

53
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:32,720
And there's no one better suited to have this conversation

54
00:02:32,720 --> 00:02:36,040
with than Professor John Lennox.

55
00:02:36,040 --> 00:02:38,120
John, it's great to have you with us.

56
00:02:38,120 --> 00:02:39,600
Welcome to Practical Wisdom.

57
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:42,240
Well, thank you very much, Samuel.

58
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:46,400
Ladies and gentlemen, thank you all for coming.

59
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:49,120
I'd just like to say how grateful I

60
00:02:49,120 --> 00:02:53,320
am to Samuel and the team that have organized this,

61
00:02:53,320 --> 00:02:59,560
because as Justin has just said, getting public discussion

62
00:02:59,560 --> 00:03:04,640
on the big ideas is increasingly important

63
00:03:04,640 --> 00:03:08,720
as our culture disintegrates by various influences that

64
00:03:08,720 --> 00:03:10,760
come around.

65
00:03:10,760 --> 00:03:14,320
Now, I want to encourage you to read Justin's book

66
00:03:14,320 --> 00:03:16,520
afterwards, and I want to tell you

67
00:03:16,520 --> 00:03:21,200
that Samuel is a formidable interviewer,

68
00:03:21,200 --> 00:03:23,160
and that we have not colluded.

69
00:03:23,160 --> 00:03:25,880
I don't know what he's going to ask me.

70
00:03:25,880 --> 00:03:28,560
So I sit here in fear and trembling,

71
00:03:28,560 --> 00:03:31,640
and look forward to the questions

72
00:03:31,640 --> 00:03:34,120
that he's going to put to me.

73
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:38,760
John, you've engaged in many debates with intellectuals

74
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:41,240
and really heavyweight thinkers, people

75
00:03:41,240 --> 00:03:45,080
like Richard Dawkins, Christopher Hitchens,

76
00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:48,120
and many other influential atheists.

77
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:52,440
Many people in this room will know you from these debates.

78
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:56,520
Can you talk a little bit about these debates?

79
00:03:56,520 --> 00:03:59,600
Which one was one of the most remarkable one?

80
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:03,520
And also, what insights have you gained

81
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:04,560
from this experience?

82
00:04:07,480 --> 00:04:11,320
I suppose one of the most remarkable ones,

83
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:14,200
and partly for a humorous reason,

84
00:04:14,200 --> 00:04:19,320
was the debate with Professor Peter Singer, who's

85
00:04:19,320 --> 00:04:21,520
one of the world's leading ethicists.

86
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:26,000
And I was invited to debate him on his home turf that

87
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,760
is in Melbourne City Hall some years ago,

88
00:04:28,760 --> 00:04:31,000
although he teaches at Princeton.

89
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:36,160
And in the opening remarks, I'm always open with audiences

90
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:39,200
and point out that my parents were Christian.

91
00:04:39,200 --> 00:04:41,440
And when he started, he said, well,

92
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:45,600
there goes my main objection against all religion.

93
00:04:45,600 --> 00:04:49,880
People stay in the religion in which they were brought up.

94
00:04:49,880 --> 00:04:52,120
And when I heard that, I thought,

95
00:04:52,120 --> 00:04:54,720
this is going to be very interesting.

96
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:58,600
Because when I got a chance to speak, I said, Peter,

97
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:02,400
I told them about my parents.

98
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:04,040
Tell me about your parents.

99
00:05:04,040 --> 00:05:05,880
Were they atheists?

100
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:07,680
Yes, he said they were atheists.

101
00:05:07,680 --> 00:05:13,440
So I said, you stayed in the faith in which you grew up then.

102
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:15,960
Oh, but he said, it isn't a faith.

103
00:05:15,960 --> 00:05:17,920
Oh, Peter, I said, I'm very sorry.

104
00:05:17,920 --> 00:05:19,200
I thought you believed it.

105
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:25,920
And cyberspace went mad at that time

106
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:29,160
that here was one of the world's leading thinkers who

107
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:34,360
didn't realize that his atheism was a belief system.

108
00:05:34,360 --> 00:05:38,160
And you notice how carefully Dr. Mariska Samuel

109
00:05:38,160 --> 00:05:39,320
introduced this.

110
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:41,800
He talked about faith in God.

111
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:44,000
Because all people are people of faith.

112
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,560
Everybody's got a worldview that they believe.

113
00:05:46,560 --> 00:05:50,400
And this really exposed one of the biggest problems

114
00:05:50,400 --> 00:05:52,880
we have in our culture, that Christians

115
00:05:52,880 --> 00:05:54,720
are regarded as people of faith.

116
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:57,320
That means they believe that there's no evidence.

117
00:05:57,320 --> 00:05:59,200
But atheists, they're not people of faith.

118
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:00,680
They're rational.

119
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:04,000
And fighting against that is one of the things

120
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,320
I've been doing for a long time.

121
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:09,080
What have I learned from it?

122
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:11,600
That's hard to assess.

123
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:14,080
I've learned that it's pretty scary debating

124
00:06:14,080 --> 00:06:16,720
some of these people, certainly that.

125
00:06:16,720 --> 00:06:22,040
And also, it has confirmed my faith enormously.

126
00:06:22,040 --> 00:06:27,040
Because spending a lot of time unpicking these arguments

127
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:30,360
as I grow older, I find them less and less intellectually

128
00:06:30,360 --> 00:06:31,920
impressive.

129
00:06:31,920 --> 00:06:35,400
But I think it's so important that we enter this debate,

130
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:39,880
or we have shows like Justin has been doing for years,

131
00:06:39,880 --> 00:06:42,360
to allow people to see both sides of the debate.

132
00:06:42,360 --> 00:06:44,680
I think that's a very healthy thing.

133
00:06:44,680 --> 00:06:48,640
And it enables people to see that Christianity has actually

134
00:06:48,640 --> 00:06:52,000
got very powerful evidence to support it.

135
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:56,040
And we need to know that evidence.

136
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:58,120
So you mentioned faith there.

137
00:06:58,120 --> 00:07:01,200
And you obviously have very interesting ideas

138
00:07:01,200 --> 00:07:03,600
on faith in God and science.

139
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:05,560
And the Canadian philosopher Charles Taylor

140
00:07:05,560 --> 00:07:07,840
has this secularization theory.

141
00:07:07,840 --> 00:07:10,080
And he wrote extensively about this.

142
00:07:10,080 --> 00:07:13,800
And he said, in ancient times, people

143
00:07:13,800 --> 00:07:16,520
needed God to explain supernatural things.

144
00:07:16,520 --> 00:07:20,160
So for example, if you had a solar eclipse,

145
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:22,040
people in ancient times would think

146
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:24,840
that would be the wrath of God manifested.

147
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:28,240
But nowadays, that science has explained that.

148
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:30,080
We don't need God anymore.

149
00:07:30,080 --> 00:07:33,280
So science has replaced God.

150
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:34,800
We know there's no mystery there.

151
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:36,640
We know how the planets move.

152
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:39,760
We can explain what happens during a solar eclipse.

153
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:42,720
And we can actually predict all of this next solar eclipse

154
00:07:42,720 --> 00:07:44,360
for the next 1,000 years.

155
00:07:44,360 --> 00:07:46,560
So science has replaced God.

156
00:07:46,560 --> 00:07:49,400
This is part of the secularization theory.

157
00:07:49,440 --> 00:07:53,360
And we live in a very secular society in the UK.

158
00:07:53,360 --> 00:07:57,480
And also, there's this God of the Gaps view,

159
00:07:57,480 --> 00:08:03,600
which says, and many atheists and thinkers will say,

160
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:06,920
look, Christians are a bit of a bit,

161
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:09,360
some perhaps more lazy thinkers.

162
00:08:09,360 --> 00:08:12,360
Because if they can't explain something,

163
00:08:12,360 --> 00:08:14,880
they just say, well, we can't explain it.

164
00:08:14,880 --> 00:08:16,840
Therefore, God did it.

165
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:20,320
And this is the label that many atheists

166
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:23,040
would put on Christian thought.

167
00:08:23,040 --> 00:08:27,200
What is your view on the God of the Gaps theory?

168
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:31,160
Well, it may apply to some people,

169
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:33,760
but I don't think it applies to me,

170
00:08:33,760 --> 00:08:34,800
as I tried to explain,

171
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:37,800
but there are really two questions hidden there.

172
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:41,720
There's this notion that God and science

173
00:08:41,720 --> 00:08:44,880
are alternatives in terms of explanation.

174
00:08:45,760 --> 00:08:47,720
For a long time, I couldn't understand

175
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:50,920
why people as bright as Stephen Hawking

176
00:08:50,920 --> 00:08:52,600
constantly said to the public,

177
00:08:52,600 --> 00:08:55,600
you've got to choose between God and science.

178
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:58,720
And I realized for a long time

179
00:08:58,720 --> 00:09:01,360
that part of the reason for that

180
00:09:01,360 --> 00:09:03,360
was they didn't understand

181
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:05,640
the nature of scientific explanation.

182
00:09:05,640 --> 00:09:08,360
Now, that may sound like a very arrogant claim

183
00:09:08,360 --> 00:09:11,840
for me to make, but actually, it's quite simple.

184
00:09:12,840 --> 00:09:15,840
We need to realize that the God explanation

185
00:09:15,840 --> 00:09:17,280
and the science explanation

186
00:09:17,280 --> 00:09:19,560
are different kinds of explanation.

187
00:09:19,560 --> 00:09:22,440
And I often give a very simple example to illustrate it,

188
00:09:22,440 --> 00:09:25,160
that even some professors can understand.

189
00:09:25,160 --> 00:09:29,320
And it's this, why is the water boiling?

190
00:09:29,320 --> 00:09:31,200
Well, because the heat energy

191
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:34,400
is agitating the molecules of water and is boiling.

192
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:37,960
Well, that's a scientific explanation,

193
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:40,480
but I could equally well say it's boiling

194
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:42,200
because I want a cup of tea.

195
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:46,360
Now, that is an agent, personal explanation.

196
00:09:46,360 --> 00:09:48,240
Now, think about those two explanations,

197
00:09:48,240 --> 00:09:51,560
they're different, but they do not compete,

198
00:09:51,560 --> 00:09:55,160
they do not conflict, they complement each other.

199
00:09:55,160 --> 00:09:56,800
And I often say to people,

200
00:09:56,800 --> 00:10:01,800
the God explanation is the agent type explanation.

201
00:10:02,320 --> 00:10:07,160
God is the explanation of why there is a universe at all

202
00:10:07,160 --> 00:10:10,120
and why there are scientists there to study it.

203
00:10:10,120 --> 00:10:13,800
He's not competing in that sense at all.

204
00:10:13,800 --> 00:10:17,680
And we need both, as I find most school children can say.

205
00:10:17,680 --> 00:10:22,680
The second thing is that many contemporary thinkers

206
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:28,040
have lost the idea of a God who's a transcendent creator

207
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:31,400
who upholds the universe.

208
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:36,400
And they think of God in terms of the Greek God of thunder.

209
00:10:37,080 --> 00:10:38,920
They couldn't explain thunder, as you said,

210
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:40,720
to the postulated God.

211
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:43,720
It's very important to realize

212
00:10:43,720 --> 00:10:47,240
that the God of the Bible is not in that category.

213
00:10:47,240 --> 00:10:51,000
There's a brilliant writer in Oxford

214
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:52,720
at one stage, Werner Yeager,

215
00:10:52,720 --> 00:10:55,840
who was an expert on the Greek gods and the Babylonian gods.

216
00:10:55,840 --> 00:10:59,000
And he made this point, which I think is very important.

217
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:02,240
He said, all the gods of the ancient philosophies

218
00:11:02,240 --> 00:11:04,680
and religions are, quote,

219
00:11:04,680 --> 00:11:07,640
descended from the heavens and the earth.

220
00:11:07,640 --> 00:11:09,320
That is they were actually part

221
00:11:09,320 --> 00:11:11,840
of the original material cosmos.

222
00:11:11,840 --> 00:11:15,880
The God of the Bible created the heavens and the earth.

223
00:11:15,880 --> 00:11:19,580
So they're completely different categories.

224
00:11:19,580 --> 00:11:20,640
Now, with that as background,

225
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:23,080
let me come to the heart of your question,

226
00:11:23,080 --> 00:11:25,760
which is the God of the gaps.

227
00:11:25,760 --> 00:11:29,480
Now, I'm allergic to this in the sense that

228
00:11:29,480 --> 00:11:31,320
I do not want people to think

229
00:11:31,320 --> 00:11:33,600
that I believe in a God of the gaps.

230
00:11:33,600 --> 00:11:36,200
So how do I deal with it?

231
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:37,920
Well, in several different ways.

232
00:11:37,920 --> 00:11:39,880
I'm going to go for the easiest one.

233
00:11:39,880 --> 00:11:44,880
And it's this, that think of Isaac Newton

234
00:11:45,320 --> 00:11:48,360
and his wonderful law of gravitation.

235
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:51,280
And I used to love explaining it to students

236
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:54,080
how you get an equation with eight symbols in it.

237
00:11:54,080 --> 00:11:55,980
And from it, you could deduce the motion

238
00:11:55,980 --> 00:11:57,600
of the planets around the sun.

239
00:11:57,600 --> 00:12:00,520
It is just brilliant stuff.

240
00:12:00,520 --> 00:12:03,400
Now, when Newton discovered that,

241
00:12:03,400 --> 00:12:08,400
did he think, right, I have now got an equation

242
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:12,520
that allows me to deduce the motion

243
00:12:12,520 --> 00:12:14,160
of the planets from it.

244
00:12:14,160 --> 00:12:17,040
I don't need God.

245
00:12:17,040 --> 00:12:18,200
No, he didn't.

246
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:20,760
He wrote what was perhaps the most brilliant book

247
00:12:20,760 --> 00:12:23,680
in the history of science at Principia Mathematica.

248
00:12:23,680 --> 00:12:26,960
And he dedicated it to with the hope

249
00:12:26,960 --> 00:12:31,160
that thinking people would see in it evidence

250
00:12:31,160 --> 00:12:33,400
for the existence of a divine intelligence

251
00:12:33,400 --> 00:12:36,520
behind the universe, because his argument was this.

252
00:12:36,520 --> 00:12:41,520
I found this wonderful mathematical description

253
00:12:41,680 --> 00:12:44,520
of what goes on in between heavy bodies

254
00:12:44,520 --> 00:12:45,560
and how they move.

255
00:12:45,560 --> 00:12:48,520
What a brilliant God who did it that way.

256
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:51,560
And it's exactly that in the way we normally think.

257
00:12:51,560 --> 00:12:54,120
If you know a lot about painting,

258
00:12:54,120 --> 00:12:57,120
you will see much more in a Rembrandt picture than I would

259
00:12:57,120 --> 00:13:00,920
who am pretty ignorant about art, although I like it.

260
00:13:00,920 --> 00:13:02,400
You can see the genius.

261
00:13:02,400 --> 00:13:04,720
If you're an engineer, you'll see much more

262
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:08,040
in a Rolls-Royce engine than I possibly would,

263
00:13:08,040 --> 00:13:11,000
because you see the evidence.

264
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:15,120
And to my mind, God is not a God of the gaps.

265
00:13:15,120 --> 00:13:20,120
He is the most powerful explanatory power

